# mairon — Code Documentation Reference
Each entry explains what the will file do, what it will import, and how it will connect to the rest of the tool.
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


# ── pyproject.toml ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The Python package configuration file. Will define the project name, version,
license, and minimum Python version (3.8+). Lists third-party dependencies:
`requests` (HTTP calls), `colorama` (terminal colors), and `bcrypt` (password
hashing). The critical entry here is [project.scripts] which maps the terminal
command `mairon` to the main() function inside mairon/main.py — this is what
allows the tool to be run by name without typing `python3 main.py`.
No APIs or imports, this is a configuration file that will be read by pip at install time.

# ── Makefile ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

A build automation file executed with `make install`. Contains three sequential
steps: (1) runs `pip install .` to install the Python package using pyproject.toml,
(2) compiles mairon/modules/dict_attack.cpp into a binary using g++ with OpenSSL
flags retrieved via `pkg-config`, and (3) calls download_rockyou() from utils.py
via a one-line Python call to set up the wordlist. Also defines `make clean`
(removes build artifacts) and `make uninstall` (removes pip package and binary).
Requires: g++, libssl-dev, pkg-config to be installed on the system.

# ── mairon/__init__.py ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Package identity file. Required by Python to treat the mairon/ folder as an
importable package. Defines three module-level constants: __version__ ("0.1.0"),
__author__, and __license__ ("GPL-3.0-or-later"). These values are not used
programmatically in v0.1 but serve as the canonical version source and are
accessible via `import mairon; mairon.__version__` if needed by future scripts.
No imports, no logic — purely declarative.

# ── mairon/utils.py ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Shared utility module. Defines paths used across the tool: MAIRON_DIR
(~/.mairon/), WORDLIST_DIR, and WORDLIST_PATH for rockyou.txt storage.
Contains two functions: get_wordlist_path() which checks three locations in
order — the local ~/.mairon/ copy, Kali Linux's pre-installed plain-text
rockyou.txt, and Kali's gzipped version — returning the first valid path found.
download_rockyou() handles the full download workflow: symlink from Kali if
available, gzip extraction if the .gz variant exists, or HTTP streaming download
from a public GitHub mirror with a live progress bar. Imports: os, sys, gzip,
shutil, requests.

# ── mairon/main.py ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Entry point and orchestrator for the entire tool. Imports all 6 analysis modules
plus report_gen, scoring, and utils. Defines the ASCII art banner (printed on
every run) and all terminal display functions (_print_breach, _print_entropy, etc.)
which apply color coding via colorama: red for failures, yellow for warnings,
green for passes. Builds the CLI argument parser via argparse, handling flags:
-a (all modules), -m (specific modules), -r (report), --offline, --wordlist,
--update-wordlist, --list. Collects each module's output into a shared `results`
dict, passes it to calculate_score(), then optionally to generate_txt_report().
Password input uses getpass() so it never echoes to the terminal.

# ── mairon/modules/__init__.py ─────────────────────────────────────────────────

Empty package marker file. Required by Python so that mairon/modules/ is treated
as a sub-package, allowing imports like `from mairon.modules.entropy import
calculate_entropy` to resolve correctly. Contains a single comment line.
No logic, no imports.

# ── mairon/modules/breach_check.py ────────────────────────────────────────────

Module 1. Implements k-anonymity breach checking against the HaveIBeenPwned
(HIBP) Pwned Passwords API (https://api.pwnedpasswords.com/range/). Hashes
the password locally with SHA-1 via hashlib, sends only the first 5 hex
characters to the API, then checks the returned list of suffix:count pairs
locally for a match — the full password and full hash never leave the machine.
Returns a dict: {found: bool, count: int, error: str|None}. Handles connection
errors, timeouts, and HTTP errors gracefully without crashing the tool.
Imports: hashlib, requests.

# ── mairon/modules/entropy.py ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

Module 2. Calculates password entropy in bits using the formula H = L × log2(R),
where L is password length and R is the size of the character set used (detected
by scanning for lowercase, uppercase, digits, and special characters — adding
26, 26, 10, and 32 to R respectively). Maps the result to one of five human-
readable ratings: Very Weak (<28 bits), Weak (<36), Reasonable (<60), Strong
(<128), Very Strong (128+), based on NIST SP 800-63B guidance. Returns a dict
with entropy, charset_size, length, rating, description, and four boolean flags
for character class presence. Imports: math only — no external dependencies.

# ── mairon/modules/pattern_detector.py ────────────────────────────────────────

Module 3. Scans the password for nine categories of predictable patterns using
regex (re module) and hardcoded lists. Detects: keyboard walks (qwerty, asdf,
12345), common dictionary words (password, dragon, iloveyou — 23 entries),
year patterns (1900–2099 via regex), repeated characters (3+ in a row), all-
digit or all-letter passwords, common suffix padding (word + 123/!/@ etc.),
predictable structures (Capital + word + digits via regex), and reversed common
words. Each detected issue is appended to an issues list. Rating is assigned
as Clean (0 issues), Medium Risk (1–2), or High Risk (3+). Imports: re only.

# ── mairon/modules/dict_attack.cpp ────────────────────────────────────────────

Module 4 — C++ component. Reads a wordlist file line by line, SHA-1 hashes
each word using OpenSSL's SHA1() function, and compares against the target hash
passed as argv[1]. Written in C++ rather than Python because sequential file
I/O combined with per-line hashing is compute-heavy — C++ with OpenSSL runs
approximately 3–5× faster than Python's hashlib for this workload, giving more
realistic crack-time simulation. Outputs exactly 3 lines to stdout: "FOUND" or
"NOT_FOUND", words checked (int), and elapsed time in seconds (float). Compiled
by the Makefile to ~/.local/bin/mairon_dict_attack using g++ -O2 with OpenSSL.
Requires: g++, libssl-dev (OpenSSL), pkg-config.

# ── mairon/modules/dict_attack.py ─────────────────────────────────────────────

Module 4 — Python wrapper. Acts as the bridge between main.py and the compiled
C++ binary. Resolves the binary path (~/.local/bin/mairon_dict_attack) and the
wordlist path (via get_wordlist_path() from utils.py). SHA-1 hashes the password
using hashlib to produce the argument for the binary. Calls the binary via
subprocess.run() with a 180-second timeout. Parses the 3-line stdout output
from the binary back into a Python dict: {found, words_checked, time_elapsed,
error}. Handles all failure cases — missing binary, missing wordlist, timeout,
and unexpected output — without crashing the tool. Imports: os, hashlib,
subprocess, and get_wordlist_path from mairon.utils.

# ── mairon/modules/mutation_engine.py ─────────────────────────────────────────

Module 5. Generates common human mutations of the password and checks each
against the HIBP breach database. Mutations produced by generate_mutations():
leet speak (a→@, e→3, o→0, s→$, t→7, l→1, b→8, g→9), all-caps, capitalized,
reversed, reversed+leet, 14 common suffixes (123, !, 2024, etc.) applied to
the original and leet variants. Each mutation is checked against HIBP using the
same k-anonymity method as breach_check.py via the internal _check_hibp() helper.
Returns a dict with the full mutations list (each with breached/count), totals,
and a rating: Low Risk (0 breached), Medium Risk (1–3), High Risk (4+). In
--offline mode, breach checks are skipped entirely. Imports: hashlib, requests.

# ── mairon/modules/hash_comparison.py ─────────────────────────────────────────

Module 6. Generates the password's hash in four algorithms and returns
educational metadata about each. MD5 and SHA-1 use Python's stdlib hashlib.
SHA-256 also uses hashlib. bcrypt uses the third-party `bcrypt` library with
cost factor 12 (current industry recommendation) and a freshly generated salt —
meaning each run produces a different bcrypt hash, which is intentional and
correct behavior. If bcrypt is not installed, a placeholder message is returned
instead of crashing. Each algorithm entry includes its approximate GPU cracking
speed (based on public Hashcat RTX 3090 benchmarks), a crackable flag, status
label, rating string, and recommended use case. Imports: hashlib, bcrypt.

# ── mairon/modules/report_gen.py ──────────────────────────────────────────────

Module 7. Writes a formatted plain-text audit report to ./reports/ in the
directory where mairon was invoked. Filename includes a timestamp (e.g.
mairon_report_20240501_143022.txt) to prevent overwrites. The _redact() helper
masks the password as first_char + asterisks + last_char before any write —
the raw password never appears in the file. Builds the report section by section
from the shared results dict: breach status, entropy stats, pattern issues table,
dict attack results, mutations table (capped at 20 rows), hash comparison block,
and a per-module score breakdown. Imports: os, datetime. No external dependencies.

# ── mairon/modules/scoring.py ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

Module 8. Aggregates results from all other modules into a single 0–100 integer
score using locked weights: Breach Check 25pts, Entropy 20pts, Pattern Detection
20pts, Dictionary Attack 15pts, Mutation Engine 10pts, Hash Comparison 10pts.
Deduction logic per module: breach found → full 25pt deduction; entropy uses a
rating-to-deduction map (Very Weak→20, Weak→15, Reasonable→8, Strong→3); patterns
deduct 5pts per issue (capped at 20); dict attack found → full 15pt deduction;
mutations deduct proportionally based on breached/total ratio; hash comparison
is informational and always returns full points. Modules that errored or were
# skipped contribute zero deduction. Final score maps to: LOW RISK (80+), MEDIUM
# RISK (55+), HIGH RISK (30+), CRITICAL RISK (<30). Imports: nothing — pure logic.
